      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why H-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>At 4 points per tile, H delivers solid value in every word it appears in. With only two H tiles in the bag, you won't see it often — but when you do, it opens up reliable scoring patterns. H is one of the most natural front-hook letters in English: add it to existing words like EAT → HEAT, ARM → HARM, OWL → HOWL, and you create two scoring words in a single play.</p>
      <p>H also combines well with high-value partners. HEX (13 pts), HAJ (13 pts), and HAZY (19 pts) leverage X, J, and Z respectively. The H+Z combination in words like HUZZAH (29 pts), HAZING (19 pts), and HAZILY (21 pts) is particularly productive because both letters reward you with significant points.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing H-Words</h2>
      <p>H is a reliable scorer that doesn't require complex setups. Here are the best ways to use it:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Front-hook aggressively:</strong> H is the king of front-hooks. Words like EAR → HEAR, OOK → HOOK, OLD → HOLD, OW → HOW create parallel scoring opportunities everywhere on the board.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Target HEX on premium squares:</strong> HEX (13 pts) on a TLS under X scores 37 points from just 3 tiles. It's one of the most efficient premium-square plays in the game.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use H with Y for consonant dumps:</strong> Words like HYMN, HYPE, HYPER, and HEAVY help clear consonant-heavy racks. The HY- combination is productive and scores well.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>SH and CH parallel plays:</strong> The SH and CH combinations form the basis of hundreds of words. Use them for parallel plays — placing SH next to an existing word often creates multiple valid two-letter intersections.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't waste H on low-value plays:</strong> Since there are only 2 H tiles, a 4-point letter shouldn't be burned on words scoring under 10 points. If your only H play scores poorly, consider whether another rack arrangement gives better value.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">H as a Hook Master</h2>
      <p>H is arguably the best front-hook letter in Scrabble. The sheer number of common words that gain validity by adding H to the front is remarkable. This makes H valuable even on tight boards where long words can't fit — you simply find an existing word, place H in front, and score for both the new word and any perpendicular crossings.</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Common H-hooks:</strong> EAR→HEAR, EAT→HEAT, OWL→HOWL, ARM→HARM, ATE→HATE, AIR→HAIR, OLD→HOLD, IT→HIT, IS→HIS</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Back-hooks with H:</strong> Adding H to the end also works — OOH, AAH, BAH, PAH, RAH — these are all valid and score the H's 4 points while forming useful parallel-play setups</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Two-Letter H-Words Every Player Must Know</h2>
